Hi Fahad,



Konstantin already gave a great example of a whole application with Views.
Note that this example re-creates the map whenever the View is re-rendered.



Another alternative would be to use the sap.ui.core.HTML control which can
host any plain HTML and takes care of moving that HTML out of the way when UI5
re-renders stuff (and of moving it back afterwards, of course).

This means the same map can stay alive safely.

(Note this does not work so well for e.g. iframes because they are reloaded by
the browser when being moved in the DOM)



And then the whole thing could be nicely wrapped inside a custom control, so
it can be re-used easily (make sure not to forget loading the Google Maps
script as shown in the first line)



Here it is (just the script part of the page - add the usual boilerplate code
around that):





  &lt;script type="text/javascript"
src="<http://maps.google.com/maps/api/js?sensor=false>"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;



 &lt;script&gt;



 // PART 1: define the new GoogleMap Control type



 sap.ui.core.Control.extend("my.GoogleMap", {

 metadata : {

 properties : { // setter and getter are created
behind the scenes, incl. data binding and type validation

 latitude: "float",

 longitude: "float"

 }

 },

 init: function(){

 this._html = new sap.ui.core.HTML({content:"&lt;div
style='height:100%;width:100%;' id='" +
this.getId()+"-map'&gt;&lt;/div&gt;"});

 },

